1
00:00:08,459 --> 00:00:11,451
派拉蒙影业巨献

2
00:00:24,478 --> 00:00:30,471
赤色分子

3
00:00:30,486 --> 00:00:33,444
导演:沃伦・比蒂

4
00:00:33,489 --> 00:00:36,481
主演:黛安・基顿

5
00:00:37,494 --> 00:00:40,486
爱德华・赫尔曼

6
00:00:41,499 --> 00:00:44,491
杰兹・库辛斯基

7
00:00:45,504 --> 00:00:48,496
杰克・尼科尔森

8
00:00:49,508 --> 00:00:52,466
保罗・索尔维诺

9
00:00:52,512 --> 00:00:55,504
莫林・斯特普尔顿

10
00:01:38,701 --> 00:01:43,559
好像是1913还是1917年 记不太清楚了
Was that in 1913 or 17? I can't remember now.

11
00:01:44,875 --> 00:01:49,608
我开始忘记所有过去认识的人
I'm beginning to forget all the people that I used to know, see?

12
00:01:54,587 --> 00:01:57,147
你问我记得路易丝・拜伦吗？
Do I remember Louise Bryant?

13
00:01:58,758 --> 00:02:02,114
当然记得，即便想忘也忘不了
Why, of course. I couldn't forget her if I tried.

14
00:02:07,602 --> 00:02:08,967
我无法…
I can't...

15
00:02:09,071 --> 00:02:12,404
我也许可以抹去我的记忆
I might sort of scratch my memory,

16
00:02:12,507 --> 00:02:14,429
但那个时刻无法忘却
but not at the moment.

17
00:02:15,411 --> 00:02:18,903
往事如烟，来了又去
You know, things go and come back again.

18
00:02:19,717 --> 00:02:22,515
那是在克里斯托弗街
It was Christopher Street,

19
00:02:23,121 --> 00:02:25,487
我当时在想…
and I was thinking about

20
00:02:26,324 --> 00:02:28,781
另外一条街道
another street down there instead,

21
00:02:28,861 --> 00:02:32,285
直到又回想起是克里斯托弗街
until it came back that it was Christopher Street.

22
00:02:32,632 --> 00:02:35,328
有时我也会有失误
Sometimes I have lapses like that.

23
00:02:37,537 --> 00:02:39,596
我已经把他们全忘记了
I'd forgotten all about them.

24
00:02:39,807 --> 00:02:41,638
他们是社会主义者？
Were they socialists?

25
00:02:43,145 --> 00:02:45,101
他们一定是
I guess they must've been,

26
00:02:45,214 --> 00:02:47,341
但我想他们根本不重要
but I don't think they were of any importance.

27
00:02:47,449 --> 00:02:49,178
我完全记不起他们了
I don't remember them at all.

28
00:02:49,519 --> 00:02:52,443
我知道杰克和玛宝・道吉交往过
I know that Jack went around with Mabel Dodge,

29
00:02:52,556 --> 00:02:55,980
后来他和另一个女孩交往
and then he went around with another gal,

30
00:02:56,093 --> 00:02:58,687
接着就是和路易丝・拜伦
and then he went around with Louise Bryant.

31
00:02:59,898 --> 00:03:02,287
来来回回换了好几轮
I know there were shifts back and forth,

32
00:03:02,368 --> 00:03:04,825
但我从没发生过这种事
but it never occurred to me...

33
00:03:05,338 --> 00:03:08,569
它侵犯不了我的个人生活
It never impinged on my own personal life.

34
00:03:08,709 --> 00:03:09,971
我喜欢棒球
I like baseball.

35
00:03:10,110 --> 00:03:12,965
我不知道外面世界的人 是如何看待他们的
I don't know what the outside world thought of them.

36
00:03:13,348 --> 00:03:15,043
但他们曾经是夫妻
But they were a couple.

37
00:03:15,717 --> 00:03:19,107
人们总会说起 路易丝拜伦和杰克・雷德
I mean, you always spoke of Louise Bryant and Jack Reed.

38
00:03:19,221 --> 00:03:23,317
我记得他跟我说过他上大学时…
I recall his telling me that he had two ambitions

39
00:03:23,427 --> 00:03:24,883
有两个远大理想
when he came to college.

40
00:03:24,995 --> 00:03:27,953
其中一个就是当选班长
One was to be elected president of his class.

41
00:03:28,066 --> 00:03:30,864
他并不认识班上的同学，也没人认识他
He didn't know anyone in the class. No one knew him.

42
00:03:30,968 --> 00:03:34,233
另外一个就是在他25岁时…
The other was to make a million dollars

43
00:03:34,473 --> 00:03:36,395
成为百万富翁
by the time he was 25.

44
00:03:36,943 --> 00:03:41,266
我对于杰克・雷德的看法 可能不同于大多数人
Now, my idea about Jack Reed is probably different from most.

45
00:03:41,414 --> 00:03:46,113
但我非常了解他 我知道他是个很有见地的人
But I knew him well. I knew he was a man of strong views.

46
00:03:46,220 --> 00:03:48,176
我知道他非常的独立
I knew he was independent.

47
00:03:48,290 --> 00:03:51,384
我有个看法，可能是错的…
And I have an idea, I may be wrong of this,

48
00:03:51,527 --> 00:03:53,620
那就是他的妻子是个社会主义者
that his wife was a Communist

49
00:03:54,130 --> 00:03:58,157
妻子影响了他，和任何人的妻子一样
and that his wife had influenced him, as any wife does,

50
00:03:58,268 --> 00:03:59,826
这点大家和我都知道
as you know and I know.

51
00:04:02,607 --> 00:04:03,801
路易丝拜伦？
Louise Bryant?

52
00:04:03,908 --> 00:04:07,730
我曾认为她是个裸露狂
Well, I thought she was something of an exhibitionist.

53
00:04:07,947 --> 00:04:11,144
不，我不是说人闲话，不要自欺欺人
No, I'm not gonna talk about people. Don't fool yourself.

54
00:04:11,618 --> 00:04:15,475
不，先生，我不是…
No, sir. I'm not... I'm not

55
00:04:16,290 --> 00:04:18,281
那种喜欢说三道四的街坊
a purveyor of neighborhood gossip, or anything of the kind.

56
00:04:18,426 --> 00:04:19,552
那不是我的工作
That's not my job.

57
00:04:20,027 --> 00:04:21,460
他沉默寡言
He was quiet.

58
00:04:22,998 --> 00:04:24,989
是个好人
He was a nice fellow.

59
00:04:25,802 --> 00:04:29,863
如果我遇到他，我会说他是个好人
I would say, if I met him, I would say he was a nice fellow.

60
00:04:30,941 --> 00:04:34,297
按照特定的标准…
He was, however, a fighting fellow

61
00:04:34,411 --> 00:04:36,299
他是个好战的人
in regards to principles.

62
00:04:36,414 --> 00:04:40,737
我说过，一个对世界状况…
I said, I think, that a guy who's always interested

63
00:04:40,853 --> 00:04:43,686
感兴趣并想改变它的人…
in the condition of the world and changing it

64
00:04:43,756 --> 00:04:45,951
自己对于拒绝或直面它…
either has no problems of his own

65
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:48,025
不会有任何问题
or refuses to face them.

66
00:04:48,495 --> 00:04:51,453
杰克，我不认为他是个花花公子
Jack... Well, I wouldn't call him a playboy,

67
00:04:51,599 --> 00:04:52,896
但有人这么认为
but some people did.

68
00:04:53,001 --> 00:04:56,994
杰克・雷德的人生短暂
Jack Reed's life, short as it was,

69
00:04:57,740 --> 00:04:59,503
如同昙花一现
happened at a time,

70
00:04:59,675 --> 00:05:03,167
我们所有人都是那个时代的受害者
and all of us, after all, are the victims of our time and place,

71
00:05:03,613 --> 00:05:07,140
作为一个记者 他本来有更好的机会…
when he had the opportunity, as a reporter,

72
00:05:07,418 --> 00:05:10,649
去某个令人兴奋，景致怡人的地方
to be in some very exciting and dramatic places.

73
00:05:10,889 --> 00:05:14,484
不是所有人都会埋在克里姆林宫
It isn't everybody can be buried in the Kremlin,

74
00:05:15,328 --> 00:05:17,660
他是唯一一个埋在那里的美国人
and he's the only American.

75
00:05:17,764 --> 00:05:20,255
出生在俄勒冈州的波特兰
Born in Portland, Oregon.

76
00:05:21,502 --> 00:05:23,424
这是不是很特别？
Now, isn't that something?

77
00:05:23,938 --> 00:05:25,963
[1915年，波特兰] -他在拥抱什么？ -一个雕像
- What's he hugging? - A statue.

78
00:05:26,107 --> 00:05:28,803
我看得出来，但它是个什么雕像？
Well, I can see that. But what's it a statue of?

79
00:05:28,910 --> 00:05:30,502
只是雕像，伍沃先生
It's just a statue, Mr. Woodward.

80
00:05:30,613 --> 00:05:32,911
-多少钱？ -75美元
- How much is it? - It's $75.

81
00:05:33,015 --> 00:05:34,903
-相片的价钱？ -没错，卢太太
- For a photograph? - That's right, Mrs. Rudisile.

82
00:05:35,018 --> 00:05:36,576
这真有趣，楚太太
This is interesting, Mrs. Trullinger.

83
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:39,314
这不仅不怎么好，而且也算不上油画
Not that it isn't very nice, but it isn't a painting.

84
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:41,618
伍沃先生，请你看看这个
Mr. Woodward, I'd like you to look at this.

85
00:05:41,726 --> 00:05:43,785
-我能看出作者的意图 -是的
- I think I see the intention here. - Yes.

86
00:05:43,895 --> 00:05:45,692
黄昏俯瞰图
Eve dominates, you see?

87
00:05:45,798 --> 00:05:47,754
梦想俯瞰梦想家
The dream dominates the dreamer.

88
00:05:48,033 --> 00:05:49,295
这个…
It's...

89
00:05:52,339 --> 00:05:54,102
我感觉比较模糊
It looks blurry to me.

90
00:05:54,308 --> 00:05:56,435
另一个看起来也有点模糊
The other one looked blurry, too.

91
00:05:56,577 --> 00:05:59,910
这是摄影师的意图，伍沃先生
I think that's the intention of the photographer, Mr. Woodward.

92
00:06:00,015 --> 00:06:01,346
什么？故意整模糊？
What? To be blurry?

93
00:06:01,450 --> 00:06:03,543
如果你用另一种观点去看…
But perhaps if you looked at it from a different point of view...

94
00:06:03,652 --> 00:06:04,812
路易丝
Louise!

95
00:06:05,588 --> 00:06:07,283
这是你吗？
This is you?

96
00:06:13,865 --> 00:06:15,162
体形真好
Lovely figure.

97
00:06:24,544 --> 00:06:26,136
路易丝，你是不是疯了？
Louise, have you taken leave of your senses?

98
00:06:26,246 --> 00:06:27,907
别傻了，保罗
Don't be a fool, Paul.

99
00:06:28,148 --> 00:06:29,945
反对自己妻子在半数熟人面前裸体…
You think I'm a fool because I object to my wife

100
00:06:30,084 --> 00:06:32,143
你竟认为我傻？
being displayed naked in front of half the people I know...

101
00:06:32,287 --> 00:06:34,118
是的，它不过是画廊的一幅艺术品
Yes. My God, it's a work of art in a gallery.

102
00:06:34,223 --> 00:06:35,247
你是怎么啦？
What's the matter with you?

103
00:06:35,391 --> 00:06:37,586
你常把波特兰看成是个 死气沉沉的地方
You used to call Portland a stuffy provincial coffin for the mind.

104
00:06:37,693 --> 00:06:38,682
它可能乏味，可能偏狭
It may be stuffy and provincial,

105
00:06:38,795 --> 00:06:40,820
但也是我赖以生计的地方
but it also happens to be a coffin where I earn a living.

106
00:06:40,931 --> 00:06:42,455
既然你可以在此谋生…
You can take your living and fill up teeth with it,

107
00:06:42,565 --> 00:06:43,998
我也可以
because I can earn my own living.

108
00:06:44,101 --> 00:06:45,090
我有自己的工作
I have my work.

109
00:06:45,202 --> 00:06:48,660
你把发表《政府公报》上的 几篇文章当作你的工作？
You consider a few articles in The Oregonian and The Gazette work?

110
00:06:48,774 --> 00:06:50,264
不，我告诉你什么才是工作，路易丝
No, I'll tell you what your work is, Louise.

111
00:06:50,375 --> 00:06:52,366
成为公众的焦点才是你的工作
It's making yourself the center of attention.

112
00:06:52,477 --> 00:06:55,640
它会让路易丝・楚林杰成为 波特兰的自由女性
It's shocking Louise Trullinger, emancipated woman of Portland.

113
00:06:55,715 --> 00:06:58,172
现在我们去向这些人道晚安 然后回家
Now, we're gonna say good night to these people and go home.

114
00:06:58,285 --> 00:07:00,583
-我要去自由主义俱乐部 -你不能去
- I'm going to the Liberal Club. - You're not going to the Liberal Club.

115
00:07:00,721 --> 00:07:02,382
-我要去，保罗 -不能去…
- I'm going to the Liberal Club, Paul. - No, you're not...

116
00:07:03,992 --> 00:07:06,847
全都很漂亮，楚太太
It's very nice, Mrs. Trullinger. All of it.

117
00:07:07,228 --> 00:07:09,788
这些话让你心满意足了吧，路易丝？
It's very gratifying to hear, isn't it, Louise?

118
00:07:09,899 --> 00:07:11,332
是不是，路易丝？
Isn't it, Louise?

119
00:07:14,571 --> 00:07:17,836
不用说也知道 谁要去自由主义俱乐部
Of course, you know who is going to be at the Liberal Club.

120
00:07:18,042 --> 00:07:20,636
美国爱国者信仰自由
Patriotic Americans believe in freedom.

121
00:07:20,845 --> 00:07:24,542
若我们不愿拿起武器维护这个传统…
And unless we are willing to take arms to defend our heritage,

122
00:07:24,650 --> 00:07:27,983
我们就无法自称为美国爱国者
we cannot call ourselves patriotic Americans!

123
00:07:29,489 --> 00:07:31,354
我为自由自豪
I'm proud to be free.

124
00:07:31,591 --> 00:07:33,456
我为自己是美国人自豪
I'm proud to be an American.

125
00:07:33,594 --> 00:07:36,358
若我们选举出来的总统…
And if the man we elected President decides

126
00:07:36,497 --> 00:07:38,294
时刻为我们的自由而担忧…
that our freedoms are being threatened

127
00:07:38,400 --> 00:07:41,358
那世界将因民主而变得安全祥和…
and that the world must be made safe for democracy,

128
00:07:41,636 --> 00:07:45,959
由此也让我知道 在爱国的行列中我并不孤单！
then I know I won't be alone in heeding the call of patriotism!

129
00:07:46,175 --> 00:07:48,302
这是场什么战争？
What is this war about?

130
00:07:48,679 --> 00:07:51,045
每个人都会有自己的答案
Each man will have his own answer.

131
00:07:51,415 --> 00:07:54,805
我也有，我等待着祖国的召唤！
I have mine. I'm ready to be called!

132
00:08:03,096 --> 00:08:05,257
今晚，我们请到了…
Now, tonight we have with us

133
00:08:05,365 --> 00:08:09,358
玛格丽特和已故的波特兰 C.J.雷德先生之子
the son of Margaret and the late C.J. Reed of Portland,

134
00:08:09,504 --> 00:08:12,302
他亲眼目睹了这场战争
who has witnessed this war first-hand.

135
00:08:12,408 --> 00:08:15,764
我认为自由主义俱乐部的全体成员…
And I, for one, see no reason why we here at the Liberal Club

136
00:08:15,878 --> 00:08:18,642
都应该听听杰克・雷德的现身说法
shouldn't listen to what Jack Reed has to say.

137
00:08:24,088 --> 00:08:27,945
你认为这场战争 是关于什么的，杰克・雷德？
What would you say this war is about, Jack Reed?

138
00:08:38,238 --> 00:08:39,432
利润
Profits.

139
00:08:41,175 --> 00:08:42,472
他说什么？
What did he say?

140
00:08:47,583 --> 00:08:50,040
雷德先生 你好，我是路易丝拜伦
Excuse me, Mr. Reed. Hello, my name is Louise Bryant

141
00:08:50,152 --> 00:08:51,107
我是个记者
and I am a journalist.

142
00:08:51,221 --> 00:08:53,485
可否花点时间接受我的采访
And I was wondering if you might have time to give me an interview.

143
00:08:53,590 --> 00:08:54,784
抱歉，不行，我不接受采访的
I'm sorry, I don't. I don't do interviews.

144
00:08:54,891 --> 00:08:57,314
前不久我曾在《冲击波》上发表过文章
I had a piece in the Blast not long ago.

145
00:08:57,862 --> 00:09:00,194
-伯克曼的《冲击波》？ -是的
- Berkman's Blast? Really? - That's right.

146
00:09:04,703 --> 00:09:06,295
你什么时候想采访？
Well, when did you want to do this interview?

147
00:09:06,406 --> 00:09:07,395
现在
Now.

148
00:09:07,507 --> 00:09:08,633
我并不住这里
I don't live here.

149
00:09:08,741 --> 00:09:10,732
-住在河边的一所屋子里 -是嘛？
- I live in a house by the river. - Oh, really.

150
00:09:10,811 --> 00:09:12,608
天哪，狡兔三窟啊
My, my, my. Two places.

151
00:09:14,982 --> 00:09:17,473
是的，这里是工作室
Yeah, I use this place as a studio.

152
00:09:18,854 --> 00:09:20,515
喜欢白色百合吗？
Do you like white lilies?

153
00:09:21,224 --> 00:09:23,021
那是我最喜欢的花
They're my favorite flowers.

154
00:09:24,060 --> 00:09:28,121
-你还没结婚吧？ -没有，我不相信婚姻
- You're not married, are you? - No, I don't think I believe in marriage.

155
00:09:28,232 --> 00:09:29,221
-你结婚了吗？ -婚姻？
- Are you married? - Marriage?

156
00:09:29,333 --> 00:09:30,823
怎么会有人相信婚姻？
How could anyone believe in marriage?

157
00:09:31,436 --> 00:09:34,200
想必你母亲看到你回波特兰一定很开心
I bet your mother's glad to see you back in Portland.

158
00:09:34,305 --> 00:09:36,762
只有我不坐牢时她才开心 这是你吗？
Just glad when I'm not in jail. Is this you?

159
00:09:36,976 --> 00:09:38,671
是的，喜欢吗？
Yes. Do you like it?

160
00:09:39,512 --> 00:09:41,844
喜欢，我觉得它们…
Yeah. I think they're...

161
00:09:42,616 --> 00:09:46,473
-有点模糊，不过这张很好 -是的
- A little blurry, but this one's very nice. - Yes.

162
00:09:46,587 --> 00:09:47,713
是的，现在…
It is. Now...

163
00:09:50,025 --> 00:09:51,980
世界经济的牟利动机…
Granted, the profit motive in the world economy

164
00:09:52,093 --> 00:09:54,048
是导致战争的根源
is a basic root cause for the war.

165
00:09:54,162 --> 00:09:56,459
你认为那些赞成战争 把动机归咎于爱国心的美国人…
Do you feel that those Americans who are pro-war

166
00:09:56,563 --> 00:10:00,191
是不是出于愤世嫉俗或者天真？
and who ascribe their motives to patriotism are cynical or naive?

167
00:10:00,300 --> 00:10:02,688
如果他们愤世嫉俗 那些玩世不恭的爱国者…
And, if they're cynical, is it the cynicism of patriots

168
00:10:02,969 --> 00:10:04,458
认为如果没有牟利动机…
who feel that without a profit motive,

169
00:10:04,570 --> 00:10:07,299
这个国家的领导层就不会涉足战争
the power structure elite of this country will not enter the war,

170
00:10:07,406 --> 00:10:08,804
即便他们认为…
even though they feel that the containment

171
00:10:08,908 --> 00:10:10,932
德国军国主义的牵制政策也许有必要…
of German militarism may be necessary for...

